1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], or YouTube [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/a6bb976f-d343-4af1-8590-d390a1117aad?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
Blockchains As Platforms
Blockchains are platforms on top of which developers can build products.=C2=
=A0
Their success depends on whether developers choose to build products on top=
 of them. As more developers build better products on blockchains, they wil=
l attract more users.
Generally, developers, in their enlightened self-interest, build the produc=
ts that they believe will make them the most money. That means building pro=
ducts that will attract the most users, or attract a smaller number of user=
s who are willing to pay them more money. Certainly, there are other consid=
erations =E2=80=93 impact, self-actualization, novelty, whatever =E2=80=93 =
but for our purposes, let=E2=80=99s assume developers build the products th=
at they think will make them the most money.=C2=A0
When choosing which platforms to build on top of, developers need to weigh =
trade-offs. What benefits does the platform offer the product, and ultimate=
ly its users, and what drawbacks does the platform present?=C2=A0
Different developers will make different trade-offs depending on what they=
=E2=80=99re building.=C2=A0
Over time, as infrastructure improves, the trade-off calculus will come out=
 in blockchains=E2=80=99 favor for more use cases.=C2=A0
Take the cloud as an example. When Amazon first built AWS, startups were ea=
rly adopters while larger companies and governments with higher security re=
quirements remained on-prem. For startups, the low upfront cost, scalabilit=
y, and ease of AWS outweighed the potential security risks and lack of full=
 control of the cloud. The cloud made previously infeasible companies feasi=
ble. For large companies and governments, the familiarity, tooling, and sec=
urity of on-prem servers outweighed AWS=E2=80=99 benefits. Over time, as Am=
azon and the other cloud providers invested in performance, tooling, and se=
curity, the drawbacks shrank as the benefits grew. Cloud usage has grown as=
 the trade-off has flipped in its favor for more and more developers.=C2=A0
The decision of whether or not to build on a blockchain depends on trade-of=
fs, too.=C2=A0
On the benefits side, blockchains offer:=C2=A0
Decentralization
Smart contracts=C2=A0
Tokens=C2=A0
Global exchange
Ownership
Governance
Verification and transparency
Permissionlessness
Composability=C2=A0
Immutability
Security
Ability to make commitments in code
But blockchains in their current form come with significant drawbacks:=C2=
=A0
Slowness
Higher costs
Clunky user experience
Limited privacy
Regulatory uncertainty
Key management difficulty
Stigmatization
Whether a developer chooses to build their product onchain depends entirely=
 on whether the benefits outweigh the drawbacks for the specific product th=
ey=E2=80=99re trying to build.
Today, according to the latest numbers from a16z=E2=80=99s State of Crypto =
Index [ https://substack.com/redirect/e24f77a1-6ad2-4920-8649-99f853eb5cf7?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], there=
 are 23.3k active developers building in crypto out of roughly 1,000x that =
many developers in the world. The drawbacks currently outweigh the benefits=
 for 99.9% of developers.=C2=A0
But for a small number of developers, the benefits outweigh the drawbacks b=
ecause blockchains allow them to do things that they could not otherwise do=
=2E=C2=A0
A significant proportion of products built on blockchains are financial =E2=
=80=93 exchanges, NFTs, and payments =E2=80=93 because they are the product=
s that couldn=E2=80=99t be built on traditional infrastructure. Slowness, h=
igher costs, and a clunky UX don=E2=80=99t matter as much as the fact that =
these products are possible to build on blockchains.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s no surprise that the most popular social product in crypto ove=
r the past year, friend.tech, is one with money baked into its mechanics =
=E2=80=93 it=E2=80=99s a product that=E2=80=99s only possible in crypto. Th=
e app crashes and the product is slow and clunky, but those drawbacks are o=
utweighed by the unique ability to make money every time someone trades you=
r keys.=C2=A0
It won=E2=80=99t always be just about money, though. As blockchains=E2=80=
=99 capabilities expand, performance improves, and drawbacks get figured ou=
t, the number of things built on blockchains grows. The more =E2=80=9Cfree=
=E2=80=9D you can make the benefits, the easier the decision becomes.=C2=A0
Bitcoin the blockchain was good at sending and receiving bitcoin the crypto=
currency. It didn=E2=80=99t attract many developers besides those who were =
philosophically aligned or wanted to build with something new, and there ar=
e few examples of popular products built on Bitcoin.=C2=A0
When Ethereum introduced smart contracts, it expanded the things that devel=
opers could do on blockchains. It increased the benefits and decreased the =
drawbacks, but it was still slow and expensive and clunky enough that it ca=
ptured mostly newly possible use cases.=C2=A0
With faster and cheaper blockchains and L2s, the trade-offs tilt further in=
 the favor of developing certain products onchain. With zero-knowledge proo=
fs that provide privacy onchain, the trade-offs tilt further in the favor o=
f developing certain products onchain. With UX improvements like embedded w=
allets, multi-party computation, and account abstraction, the trade-offs ti=
lt further in the favor of developing certain products onchain.=C2=A0
Take social apps. web3 social products like Farcaster and Lens won=E2=80=99=
t win by being Twitter, but decentralized. Users care about speed, experien=
ce, and dopamine more than they care about decentralization.=C2=A0
But as the infrastructure improves, the benefits of building on blockchains=
 begin to outweigh the drawbacks. In August, Farcaster moved from Ethereum =
Mainnet to Optimism, a faster and cheaper Layer 2. It integrated NFT mintin=
g directly in casts with Zora and song minting directly in casts with sound=
=2Exyz.
It=E2=80=99s reducing speed and cost drawbacks while leaning into the benef=
its of composability. The trade-off tilts further in favor of developing on=
chain.=C2=A0
There are plenty of products that would benefit from the unique features of=
 crypto if the drawbacks were low enough. Verification, for example, become=
s more important with the rise of generative AI, as does the ability to own=
 your own models [ https://substack.com/redirect/026267e0-fa6d-49ed-a09d-ad=
4a9ef505e7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] and tap into decentralized compute. Tokens and value exchange can be u=
seful for loyalty and rewards products. When transactions cost $50 in gas f=
ees and took minutes to finalize, the drawbacks weren=E2=80=99t low enough.=
=C2=A0
But with cheaper, faster transactions and UX improvements, those products s=
tart to make sense.=C2=A0
Blackbird [ https://substack.com/redirect/6eb3454b-ec89-422a-a19b-aa75425be=
d09?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], f=
or example, is a restaurant loyalty app founded by Resy co-founder Ben Leve=
nthal. It=E2=80=99s built on Coinbase=E2=80=99s Base L2 and uses embedded w=
allets so that it=E2=80=99s fast, cheap, and doesn=E2=80=99t feel like a cr=
ypto app. It feels like a regular app, with crypto benefits, and it=E2=80=
=99s rapidly expanding with great bars and restaurants in NYC. Soon, it wil=
l be crazy to launch a loyalty product that doesn=E2=80=99t use crypto.=C2=
=A0
In short, as crypto=E2=80=99s infrastructure continues to improve, more and=
 more developers will find that its benefits outweigh its drawbacks and dec=
ide to build onchain.=C2=A0
This is the simplest way I=E2=80=99ve come up with to think about what use =
cases currently make sense in crypto and which don=E2=80=99t yet, and the s=
implest way to track progress in the space.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s as much art as science, since developers will have to make a j=
udgment call on what users will care about more. Some will build products o=
nchain believing the trade-off has flipped in blockchains=E2=80=99 favor, o=
nly to realize that the benefits don=E2=80=99t quite outweigh the drawbacks=
=2E=C2=A0
I think that=E2=80=99s what Dani Grant and Nick Grossman at USV were descri=
bing in their 2018 blog post, The Myth of the Infrastructure Phase [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/6a0f70c4-8cfd-42d5-a271-8b579680cf84?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: =E2=80=9CFirst, app=
s inspire infrastructure. Then that infrastructure enables new apps.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0
It takes people being a little early and trying things that don=E2=80=99t q=
uite make sense yet to show other developers which drawbacks need to be att=
acked next.=C2=A0
But the drawbacks are being addressed. During the bear market, crypto has i=
mproved most of the drawbacks I listed above:
Slowness =E2=86=92 faster L2s like Optimism, Base, zkSync and L1s like Sola=
na, Aptos, and Sui
Higher costs =E2=86=92 cheaper L2s like Optimism, Base, zkSync and L1s like=
 Solana, Aptos, and Sui=C2=A0
Clunky user experience =E2=86=92 account abstraction, embedded wallets, MPC
Limited privacy =E2=86=92 zK proofs and privacy-focused L1s like Aleo and L=
2s like Aztec
Regulatory uncertainty =E2=86=92 work-in-progress but good wins in court
Key management difficulty =E2=86=92 companies like Bastion [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/3710b179-e157-4981-9a59-5420eef7b397?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (a portfolio company)
Stigmatization =E2=86=92 will come with more good products=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s still a ton of improvement left to be made. Onchain actions=
 need to get nearly as cheap as fast as offchain actions for the benefits t=
o outweigh the drawbacks for many use cases. Developers will need to be tho=
ughtful about which actions need to be onchain, which can take place offcha=
in, and the best ways to build experiences that combine the two.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99ll likely never get to a world in which everything is built onch=
ain. For some products, crypto=E2=80=99s benefits might not matter and migh=
t even be counterproductive. That=E2=80=99s OK.=C2=A0
But over time, as infrastructure developers attack crypto=E2=80=99s drawbac=
ks, and app developers get crypto=E2=80=99s benefits for closer to free, I =
expect that we=E2=80=99ll see a surprising amount of products move onchain.
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/5de6dc33-e116-4c1d-80f4-978f9=
f3b2927?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for editing!
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox with the =
Weekly Dose on Friday!
Thanks for reading,
Packy

